  <h2>The problem nobody was solving</h2>

  <p>
    Women in golf face a specific, universal, quietly embarrassing problem. Showing up
    at a new course without knowing the dress code. The rules are real. They're course
    specific, enforced, and often the difference between being welcomed and turned away
    at the bag drop.
  </p>

  <p>
    But the rules are buried in PDFs, missing from websites, never aggregated anywhere,
    and almost never written from a woman's perspective. The existing options were
    generic golf directories built by men, for men. Course databases that list yardage
    and green fees. Nothing that answers the actual question women ask before every new
    round: <em>what do I wear?</em>
  </p>

  <h2>The insight</h2>

  <p>
    This wasn't a dress code directory problem. It was a style intelligence problem.
    The opportunity wasn't "here are the rules." It was <em>here's how to show up as
    yourself, within the rules, on every course you'll ever play.</em>
  </p>

  <p>
    Utility earns the right for identity. The lookup is the hook. The Style Planner is
    the product. The brand position is a woman's POV on golf in 2026.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    Tagline: <em>Know before you go.</em>
  </blockquote>

