  <h2>The bet</h2>

  <p>
    The conventional path: hire a developer, build for six months, launch something.
    Course Code went a different direction entirely. The thesis: a solo founder with
    the right AI infrastructure can operate at the output level of a small, highly
    aligned team. Not by using AI as a tool, but by restructuring the entire operating
    model around AI.
  </p>

  <p>
    The distinction matters. Using AI means faster prompts, better copy, autocomplete.
    An AI co-founder means autonomous execution authority, real accountability, defined
    decision rights, and a persistent identity that shows up to work every day.
  </p>

  <p>
    I wrote about how this works in detail. <a href="/ai" class="text-ink hover:text-orange border-b border-ink/30 hover:border-orange transition-colors">Read the AI operating model →</a>
  </p>

  <h2>The product</h2>

  <h3>Free tier</h3>
  <p>
    Dress code lookup for 4,659 courses across all 50 states. Course vibe ratings
    (casual, smart casual, traditional, strict). Policy specifics (collars, sleeveless,
    denim, leggings, hat rules). Look Books, the community-powered style boards that
    are public by default and shareable. Course search by state or name. Verified dress
    codes with badge indicators. Community corrections to keep the data fresh.
  </p>

  <h3>Pro tier ($6.99 a month, or $39 a year with 53% savings)</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Style Planner.</strong> A 4-step wizard that takes the course, the date,
    the occasion, and your style preferences and builds a complete outfit using real
    weather data and shoppable products.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Look Books.</strong> A personal golf style archive. Save looks, organize
    boards by course or season, share by link, discover what the community is wearing
    everywhere.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Style Search.</strong> Skip the wizard. Search and browse golf products
    directly, filter by what you care about, save favorites to any Look Book.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Real-weather styling.</strong> Outfit recommendations built around the
    actual forecast for your tee time, not generic seasonal advice.
  </p>
  <p>
    Seven-day free trial. No card charged until day eight.
  </p>

  <h3>The Woman-Forward Score</h3>
  <p>
    On every course page, women rate four things specific to the women's experience:
    welcome factor, facilities, course condition, pace of play. With optional detail
    questions: were the forward tees in good shape? Did the pro shop have women's gear?
    Were playing partners welcoming? Is the bathroom accessible on the back nine?
  </p>
  <p>
    Competitors won't easily replicate this because they weren't asking these questions
    in the first place.
  </p>

  <h2>The viral loop</h2>

  <p>
    Public Look Books are shareable by link to anyone. No login required to browse.
    "Steal the Look" prompts non-users to sign up. Signup leads to a free trial of
    Style Planner. The style loop feeds itself. Walls kill sharing. Let people share
    first, monetize the upstream behavior.
  </p>

