  <h2>What I learned</h2>

  <h3>About the AI co-founder model</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>The bottleneck shifts, not disappears.</strong> You stop being blocked on
    "how long will this take to build" and start being blocked on "exactly what do I
    want this to do." Spec quality becomes the most important skill you have.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Give AI real authority, not just suggestions.</strong> An AI that can only
    advise is a better search engine. An AI with commit rights, assigned tickets, and
    QA responsibility is a collaborator. The difference is accountability architecture.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Human judgment concentrates, not diminishes.</strong> When AI handles
    execution, every decision that stays with you becomes more consequential. Brand,
    tone, pricing, who you're building for. These can't be delegated. You get to be
    only a decision-maker.
  </p>

  <h3>About building the product</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Utility earns the right for identity.</strong> The dress code lookup is the
    hook. Style Planner is the product. But you can't lead with Style Planner. You have
    to earn trust with the thing that solves the immediate, concrete problem first.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Content quality beats content volume.</strong> 4,659 courses sounds
    impressive until a user hits one with wrong information. Verified Silver and Gold
    courses build more trust than algorithmically generated ones. The tiered content
    system (Bronze, Silver, Gold) is built around that truth.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Public-first is the growth engine.</strong> Look Books shareable without
    login is how organic distribution happens. Walls kill sharing. Let people share
    first, monetize the upstream behavior.
  </p>

  <h2>The meta-point</h2>

  <p>
    Course Code is a product case study. It's also a proof of concept for a new way to
    found a company. The question every product leader should be asking in 2026 isn't
    "how do I use AI to work faster." It's "how do I redesign the operating model of
    this business around what AI can actually do?"
  </p>

  <p>
    I built a live product, got to paying customers, and shipped a complete Phase 1
    roadmap as a solo founder, on timeline, by treating that question seriously.
    That's the case study.
  </p>

